class="MsoNormal"><i><font face="arial, sans-serif">We are typically looking for Juniors (some Sophomores) to work a paid ($21.00 per hour) internship for 10-12 weeks over the summer. Students are given a project to work on throughout the internship, a mentor while onsite, regular 1:1s / Check-Ins with department heads, and at the conclusion of their program they are required to present on their project, progress made, results, etc. </font></i></p><p class="MsoNormal"><i><font face="arial, sans-serif"><br></font></i></p><p class="MsoNormal"><i><font face="arial, sans-serif">There are certainly career opportunities upon completion of the program, assuming performance during the program has met expectations. In some cases, students with a lighter school workload have been able to work PT hourly in our IT Associate role, while they are still in school. While others have been hired in the FT salary IT Trainee role, upon graduation. They would spend approx. one year in the Trainee role, acquiring the required skills/knowledge needed, as most of our entry level Java, Business Analyst, etc. type roles require one year of experience. The most recent class of interns we are proud to say we have hired 5 of the 6, and very likely going to hire the 6<sup>th</sup> upon graduation!</font></i><span style="font-size:11pt;font-family:Calibri,sans-serif;font-size:11pt"></span></p><p class="MsoNormal"><i><font face="arial, sans-serif"><br></font></i></p></div>William Turkett</div></div>\r\n' +

This talk provides a roadmap to guide you through this dynamic environment, offering strategies for building a successful career. Drawing on 15+ years of cybersecurity experience at leading tech companies, we&#39;ll address key questions about working in the field, career advancement, remote work, and the impact of AI, and provide practical, actionable insights for all tech roles.</div><div class="gmail_default"><br></div><div class="gmail_default"><div><div class="gmail_default"><font size="4" color="#7f6000"><b><u>New Section - CSC 191 C Unix Systems Programming in the Fall</u></b></font></div></div><div><div class="gmail_default">A new section of CSC 191 C - Unix Systems Programming (3hrs) has been added to the Fall 2025 course schedule! 12 seats are reserved for CS majors and this eligibility rule will be released on April 10. </div><div class="gmail_default"><br></div><div class="gmail_default"><font color="#0000ff">TR 3:30 PM - 4:45 PM in Manc 022 by Dr. Daniel Canas </font></div></div><div class="gmail_default"><font color="#0000ff"><br></font></div><div class="gmail_default"><font size="4" face="arial, sans-serif" color="#7f6000"><u><b><span style="font-variant-ligatures:no-contextual">Teacher-Scholar Forum - </span>Center for the Advancement of Teaching</b></u></font></div><div class="gmail_default"><font color="#0000ff"><br></font></div><div class="gmail_default"><div>Please join the Center for the Advancement of Teaching for our inaugural <a href="https://cat.wfu.edu/programsandservices/keynoteevents/2025conference/" target="_blank">Teacher-Scholar Forum</a> on April 29th and 30th. Inspired by the CAT’s Inclusive Teaching Conference and made possible through a partnership with the Office of the Provost and the Office of Research and Sponsored Programs, this annual event will bring together faculty from across our schools to learn together and celebrate the teacher-scholar ideal.</div><div><br></div><div>This year we are bringing Jim Lang to campus for a series of workshops over three days.
